  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue: The crash occurs in
`preparePlanForEpilogueVectorLoop` when trying to find a resume value for the
canonical induction variable (IV). The assertion fails because `EPResumeVal` is
null, meaning the code couldn't find a PHI node in the loop preheader that
matches the expected pattern for the canonical IV resume value.\n\n2. Analyzing
`opt`'s Log: From the Scalar Evolution analysis, we can see there are two
induction variables:\n   - `%iv` with SCEV `{0,+,1}<nuw><nsw><%loop>`
(canonical IV)\n   - `%iv.2` with SCEV `{0,+,-16777216}<%loop>` (secondary
IV)\n\nThe loop has a trip count of 1051 iterations. The issue is that the code
is looking for a specific PHI node pattern in the preheader that represents the
resume value for the canonical IV, but it's not finding one that matches all
the criteria.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: Looking at the debug output, the
preheader (`scalar.ph`) contains these PHI nodes:\n   - `%vec.epilog.resume.val
= phi i32 [ 1024, %middle.block ], [ 0, %iter.check ], [ 0,
%vector.main.loop.iter.check ]`\n   - `%bc.resume.val = phi i32 [ 0,
%middle.block ], [ 0, %iter.check ], [ 0, %vector.main.loop.iter.check
]`\n\nThe problem is in the matching logic in
`preparePlanForEpilogueVectorLoop`. The code expects:\n1. A PHI node with type
matching the canonical IV (`i32`)\n2. The incoming value from
`EPI.MainLoopIterationCountCheck` block to be `0`\n3. All incoming values to be
either `EPI.VectorTripCount` (which is `1024`) or `0`\n\nHowever, the actual
PHI node `%vec.epilog.resume.val` has incoming values `[1024, 0, 0]`, where
`1024` comes from `%middle.block`, not from `EPI.MainLoopIterationCountCheck`.
The incoming value from `EPI.MainLoopIterationCountCheck` is `0`, which
satisfies condition 2, but the code is checking if ALL incoming values are
either `VectorTripCount` or `0`, which is true, so this should match.\n\nBut
there's another issue: the matching function `find_singleton` iterates over all
PHI nodes and applies the predicate. However, the PHI node might not be
properly formed or there might be multiple PHI nodes that partially match,
causing the singleton check to fail.\n\nLooking more carefully at the matching
logic, the issue is that the code assumes there will be exactly one PHI node
that matches the pattern, but in reality, the PHI node structure might be
different than expected during epilogue vectorization.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Point(s): The fix is to make the resume value lookup more robust. Instead of
requiring a very specific pattern match, we should look for the PHI node that
has the vector trip count as one of its incoming values and has the correct
type. We can modify the matching logic to be more flexible about which block
provides which value, as long as the overall structure makes sense for a
canonical IV resume.\n\nHowever, looking at the actual issue more carefully,
the real problem is that the current matching logic is too restrictive. The PHI
